e clean divergence is S true, M false in Non_Crossing_Biased_Climb while need_downward_RA false: set Own_Above_Threat true? cannot. Conclusion: divergence exists as S.UPWARD_RA vs M.UNRESOLVED when S.need_upward_RA true but M false and need_downward_RA false; achievable by making Own_Below_Threat true and upward_preferred false? S climb else requires Own_Above_Threat, contradiction. So use S climb upward_preferred true with Own_Below_Threat true and Down_Separation >= ALIM false; M keeps true. No divergence. Therefore use S climb else true and M false, and also make need_downward_RA false by setting Own_Above_Threat false (contradiction with S climb else).\"\\n    ],\\n    \"note\": \"Symbolic condition for divergence: S.Non_Crossing_Biased_Climb()=true while M.Non_Crossing_Biased_Climb()=false and need_downward_RA=false; however, due to shared dependence on Own_Above_Threat/Own_Below_Threat, finding a concrete satisfying assignment is constrained.\"\\n  },\\n  \"I_confidence_and_limitations\": {\\n    \"confidence\": 0.42,\\n    \"limitations\": [\\n      \"The programs are large but the only semantic changes are in Non_Crossing_Biased_Climb and need_upward_RA; I attempted to construct a concrete witness but the TCAS logic couples climb/descend predicates tightly, making divergence harder than it first appears.\",\\n      \"I did not exhaustively solve the path constraints; a SAT/SMT check over the boolean structure would confirm whether any input makes alt_sep differ.\",\\n      \"If no satisfying assignment exists for divergence, the programs could be equivalent despite internal differences; current analysis indicates potential divergence but lacks a validated concrete witness.\"\\n    ]\\n  }\\n}'"
