sing_Biased_Descend can be true, but D1 simultaneously removes the explicit Own_Above_Threat requirement at the call site; the net effect still allows divergences (and also changes behavior even when D2 makes the function stricter).\"\\n    },\\n    \"path_specific\": {\\n      \"divergence_paths\": [\\n        \"Paths where enabled && ((tcas_equipped && intent_not_known) || !tcas_equipped) is true and need_upward_RA is false, but S and M disagree on need_downward_RA due to D2 (and/or D1).\"\\n      ],\\n      \"non_divergence_paths\": [\\n        \"Any path where the guarded block is not entered (both output UNRESOLVED).\",\\n        \"Paths where both need_upward_RA and need_downward_RA are true in both programs (both output UNRESOLVED).\",\\n        \"Paths where both need_upward_RA and need_downward_RA are false in both programs (both output UNRESOLVED).\"\\n      ]\\n    }\\n  },\\n  \"E_interaction_analysis\": {\\n    \"summary\": \"The mutant introduces two coordinated changes around downward RA logic. D2 strengthens Non_Crossing_Biased_Descend by adding explicit altitude-order constraints; D1 removes the separate Own_Above_Threat gate at the call site. These do not mask each other: D2 can make M return false where S would return true (causing output divergence), and D1 can make M consider downward RA in cases S would block (though D2 may limit some of those cases). Overall, at least one feasible input yields different printed alt_sep.\",\\n    \"explicit_masking_statement\": \"No interaction masking (no bug cancels the other to restore source behavior on all paths).\"\\n  },\\n  \"F_surviving_divergences_reaching_output\": [\\n    {\\n      \"difference_ids\": [\\n        \"D2\"\\n      ],\\n      \"how_reaches_output\": \"Choose inputs where S\\'s Non_Crossing_Biased_Descend is true in the else-branch while Own_Tracked_Alt < Other_Tracked_Alt; in M the added conjunct (Other_Tracked_Alt <= Own_Tracked_Alt) forces it false, flipping need_downward_RA and thus 