            "text/plain": [
              "'{\\n  \"answer\": \"No\",\\n  \"one_liner\": \"No, outputs are not equivalent and there is no masking between bugs; the mutant can produce UPWARD_RA where the source produces UNRESOLVED due to weakened climb logic and removal of an Own_Below_Threat guard.\",\\n  \"A_observable_output_variables\": [\\n    \"stdout printed value of alt_sep_test() (0/1/2)\",\\n    \"process exit code (0 on normal path, 1 on argc error)\"\\n  ],\\n  \"B_differences_identified\": [\\n    {\\n      \"id\": \"D1\",\\n      \"description\": \"Non_Crossing_Biased_Climb upward_preferred branch logic changed: S returns !(Own_Below_Threat()) || (Own_Below_Threat() && !(Down_Separation >= ALIM())); M returns (Own_Below_Threat() && !(Down_Separation >= ALIM())) only.\",\\n      \"directly_affected\": [\\n        \"result in Non_Crossing_Biased_Climb() when upward_preferred is true\",\\n        \"predicate value of Non_Crossing_Biased_Climb()\"\\n      ],\\n      \"immediate_effect\": \"In M, when upward_preferred is true and Own_Below_Threat() is false, Non_Crossing_Biased_Climb() becomes false, whereas in S it becomes true.\"\\n    },\\n    {\\n      \"id\": \"D2\",\\n      \"description\": \"alt_sep_test need_upward_RA computation changed: S uses Non_Crossing_Biased_Climb() && Own_Below_Threat(); M uses Non_Crossing_Biased_Climb() (drops Own_Below_Threat guard).\",\\n      \"directly_affected\": [\\n        \"need_upward_RA\"\\n      ],\\n      \"immediate_effect\": \"In M, need_upward_RA can be true even when Own_Below_Threat() is false, provided Non_Crossing_Biased_Climb() is true.\"\\n    }\\n  ],\\n  \"C_propagation_analysis\": {\\n    \"D1\": \"D1 changes the return of Non_Crossing_Biased_Climb() on the upward_preferred path. This return value flows into alt_sep_test() as part of need_upward_RA (directly in M; conjuncted with Own_Below_Threat in S). It can therefore change the need_upward_RA boolean, which then affects the alt_sep selection (UNRESOLVED vs UPWARD_RA vs DOWNWARD_RA). Control flow impact: it does not change whether the main if(enabled && ...) is entered, but it changes which RA is selected inside that block.\",\\n    \"D2\": \"D2 directly changes need_upward_RA. need_upward_RA participates in the decision tree: if (need_upward_RA && need_downward_RA) alt_sep=UNRESOLVED; else if (need_upward_RA) alt_sep=UPWARD_RA; else if (need_downward_RA) alt_sep=DOWNWARD_RA; else UNRESOLVED. Thus any change in need_upward_RA can propagate to the observable output alt_sep. Control flow impact: only within the RA selection chain; it can flip which branch is taken and therefore the printed integer.\"\\n  },\\n  \"D_masking_analysis\": {\\n    \"overwrite\": {\\n      \"D1\": \"Not overwritten: Non_Crossing_Biased_Climb() result is returned and used; no later assignment restores the source value.\",\\n      \"D2\": \"Not overwritten: need_upward_RA is assigned once per call and then used to set alt_sep; no later overwrite equalizes behavior.\"\\n    },\\n    \"control_flow\": {\\n      \"D1\": \"Only relevant when upward_preferred is true (Inhibit_Biased_Climb() > Down_Separation). If upward_preferred is false, D1 is control-flow masked because both programs use the same else-branch expression.\",\\n      \"D2\": \"Only relevant when the outer guard in alt_sep_test is true: enabled && ((tcas_equipped && intent_not_known) || !tcas_equipped). If that guard is false, both return UNRESOLVED and D2 is control-flow masked.\"\\n    },\\n    \"output\": {\\n      \"D1\": \"Not output-masked in general because it can change need_upward_RA and thus alt_sep. However, on some paths it may be output-masked if need_downward_RA is simultaneously true in both programs, forcing UNRESOLVED in both (need_upward_RA && need_downward_RA).\",\\n      \"D2\": \"Not output-masked in general because it can directly cause alt_sep to become UPWARD_RA in M while S remains UNRESOLVED.\"\\n    },\\n    \"interaction\": {\\n      \"D1_D2\": \"No interaction masking that restores equivalence: D1 tends to reduce Non_Crossing_Biased_Climb() in cases where Own_Below_Threat is false, while D2 tends to increase need_upward_RA by removing the Own_Below_Threat guard. These do not cancel universally; there exist inputs where D1 is irrelevant (upward_preferred false) and D2 alone causes divergence.\"\\n    },\\n    \"path_specific\": {\\n      \"key_diverging_path\": \"Choose upward_preferred = false so D1 is masked, but make Non_Crossing_Biased_Climb() true via the else-branch (Own_Above_Threat && Cur_Vertical_Sep>=MINSEP && Up_Separation>=ALIM). Then set Own_Below_Threat false (implied by Own_Above_Threat true). In S, need_upward_RA = Non_Crossing_Biased_Climb && Own_Below_Threat = true && false = false; in M, need_upward_RA = true. If also need_downward_RA is false, outputs differ (UNRESOLVED vs UPWARD_RA).\"\\n    }\\n  },\\n  \"E_interaction_analysis\": {\\n    \"summary\": \"Two changes affect the upward RA decision. D1 modifies Non_Crossing_Biased_Climb only on the upward_preferred branch; D2 removes an Own_Below_Threat conjunct in alt_sep_test. They do not mask each other: by selecting upward_preferred=false, D1 is control-flow masked, leaving D2 to create a surviving divergence. Conversely, when upward_preferred=true and Own_Below_Threat=false, D1 makes Non_Crossing_Biased_Climb false in M (vs true in S), but D2 simultaneously removes the Own_Below_Threat guard; this combination does not guarantee equal outputs and can still diverge depending on need_downward_RA.\"\\n  },\\n  \"F_surviving_divergences_reaching_output\": [\\n    {\\n      \"difference_ids\": [\\n        \"D2\"\\n      ],\\n      \"how\": \"With upward_preferred=false and Non_Crossing_Biased_Climb() true (else-branch), S forces need_upward_RA false due to Own_Below_Threat=false, while M sets need_upward_RA true; if need_downward_RA is false, alt_sep becomes UNRESOLVED in S and UPWARD_RA in M, changing the printed output.\"\\n    }\\n  ],\\n  \"G_final_verdict\": \"Non